caption: Food was great! My wife had Chicken and Waffles. Had a nice spice and was "incredible".  Best chicken and Waffles. I had the Loaded Breakfast Biscuits.  They were great. Great tasting and very filling. Server was friendly but not very attentive after our food was served.

Shared a great dinner with friends last evening. Our server Steven was a delight.  Dining room was full, but staged at 25% per current Covid restrictions.  Everyone was wearing masks. We all felt safe and really enjoyed a wonderful, unrushed experience.  Service, food and wine were exceptional.

With the limits on in-door dining,  took advantage of ordering one of their weekly special feast dinners.  This time it was the Southern Fried Chicken Feast - and what a joy -!!!!    From start to finish - and so much food we are still enjoying some of the left overs.     Definitely a repeat coming soon!

Great experience both in terms of the quality of the food and the customer service. I did a pick up Thanksgiving meal this year and was greeted with so much warmth by the team! It was easy and delicious, and also nice to get to experience a different take on the Thanksgiving turkey (Covid silver linings). I can't wait to get back here for their great standard fare once we are able to join each other in the dining room again!

I had the opportunity today to truly enjoy the Thanksgiving Feast offering from Bistro Bis. The meal itself was outstanding - thoughtfully composed with just the right portioning for one, which was hard to find for this unique covid-19 Thanksgiving! In addition to the food being excellent, I have to also commend the restaurant's embrace of the delivery business model. It was a flawless experience to order on Tock, and although I was concerned about the Postmates delivery because it was a third party, that part was also flawless. The packaging insured that everything arrived intact and it was all well labeled with preparation instructions for reheating.It is important to support our local businesses through delivery and carry out during this time, and I'm genuinely happy to accept some bumps in the road with businesses that typically are optimized to operate in person as they adapt to online operations, but I am happy to say that none of those bumps existed here! I will certainly be placing subsequent orders and make it a point to visit in person once it is safer to do so!

Great place for an expensive meal and drinks. I hear that senators have lunch here, but for everyone else, this is probably very much a 'special occasion' kind of place.  My dinner was great - the French onion soup was thick and oozing (quite literally) with flavor.  The Beef Short Rib Bourguignon was small, but filling, flavorful and well-presented. I'd warn you about the skin and flabby pieces on the bottom, but that's what makes it so aromatic and adds juices to the mix. Otherwise the meat was pure delight and falling apart at a touch of a fork.  Perhaps I wish there were more mashed potatoes on the plate, but they leveled it off with excellent trumpet mushrooms and thick, crunchy and crispy bacon lardon, pearl onions, and pommes mousseline, so I have no beef with the chef at all.  Oh, and you can't leave without trying at least one bite of the most delicious Opera Cake, but you won't be able to stop at one...I guarantee it!

I was in town for technical training, and was dining on the company dime, so price wasn't that much of a detriment.  I had read great reviews on this restaurant online, and had elected it as the final dinner on my trip (I like to save the best for last).  When I arrived, a waiter engaged me.  I explained that this was my first trip to a French restaurant, and that I was looking for the complete immersion experience.  He suggested a 7 course sampler meal, which ended up being more of an event.  I cant readily recollect every serving which was set in front of me, but each was a delight.  My final dish was Bananas Foster, and let me tell you... the s**t was bananas, b-a-n-a-n-a-s (ain't that right Gwen).  I don't think they could have presented a better delicacy.  It was the perfect compliment to the previous six courses.  Swoop Says: How do you say 'Bon apptit' in French?  I am all compliments.  They even used a tiny broom to sweep the crumbs from my table.  How precious is that?

Deserted nicest part of meal.

I think of Bistro Bis mainly as a work breakfast place, but I've tried it out for lunch a few times, and overall, it's a fine location for a business lunch, but it's overpriced there are better French restaurants in DC.  Even though this restaurant is technically located inside a hotel, I get the sense that most of the diners are not staying there. The breakfast crowd is somewhat busy, but the lunch crowd when Congress is in session is completely full. I imagine that when Congress is not in session, the place is definitely not as busy.  The breakfast here is not very "French." It's just general egg dishes and stuff like that, and it's fine for a working breakfast. The lunch has more "French" highlights, and most recently I ordered the beef bourguignon. Honestly, for $19 I expected something more substantial. Compared to Le Diplomate, this one pales in comparison. The beef was cooked very well, but it was more sized like and appetizer and not an entrée. So if you just ordered this dish, like I did, you don't leave very full. For tourists, I think this restaurant is overpriced.  Overall, this is a business restaurant. The service is punctual and rather formal, but it's a nice place.

I took my wife here for our first anniversary and we were not disappointed. From start to finish, the food was amazing. I am usually the guy saying it was good but not worth xx.xx. Not tonight. Delicious.

Been there twice and I have to say...they remain an underrated restaurant, despite the amount.  Hosts were friendly, waiters knew their stuff (even recommended against getting something),  I enjoy the spicy Korean meal every now and again, but it's a cop out when quality foods are over-spiced and flavored and true flavors are hidden (ie bacon wrapped scallops er bacon wrapped anything for that matter).  Great work, we'll definitly be coming back there soon.

My wife and I went to Bistro Bis for our anniversary and they made it a wonderful one.  They had a special booth reserved for us when we got there.  We arrived about 1/2 and hour before our reservation and were seated immediately.  Our waiter was very gracious and was around just the right amount -- there when you need, but not constantly hanging around.  We got the halibut and the Duck au Rhubarb.  The Halibut was good, but not as flavorful as we had expected.  The Duck was wonderful! A very creative unique blend of flavors.  The watercress soup was a scrumptious appetizer and served beautifully at the table.  Though we only ordered one soup to share, the waiter gave us a second soup free.  Also, the chef sent out a free serving of delicious baked macaroni and cheese.  On top of all of that the waiter sent us a complimentary desert plate with "Happy Anniversary" written in chocolate syrup on it.  All in all, this was a wonderful restaurant and I would recommend it to anyone.  The only thing that was less than stellar in any way was that the restaurant was a bit noisy, but not so much that it was terribly distracting.

Whadd'ya' call a restaurant where the waiters speak no French and the menu is all in English?  ... "restaurant", not a French restaurant as the category suggests.  That said, the food and service were excellent, not cheap by any means.  It was rather noisy for comfortable conversation across the table.  Overall, the Bistro Bis was not without its flaws but a very pleasant experience nonetheless.
